South African Stocks: Gijima, Old Mutual, Trematon, Telkom

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a   a n d   M i k e   C o h e n
-- 
2011-04-01T16:25:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-01/south-african-equity-market-gijima-group-impala-platinum-move.html
South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE  Africa  All
Share Index rose 181.26, or 0.6 percent, to 32,385.32 by the 5
p.m. close in Johannesburg, bringing the week’s gain to 2.5
percent.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Beige Holdings Ltd. (BEG)  , a pharmaceuticals and
cosmetics manufacturer, offered shareholders the right to buy a
total of 25 million preference shares. Beige fell 1 cent, or 20
percent, to 4 cents.  Gijima Group Ltd. (GIJ)  , a South African computer-
services company, jumped the most since Jan. 26, 2009, rallying
9 cents, or 15 percent, to 71 cents. Gijima said it was involved
in discussions that may affect its shares and that it was
reviewing its business strategy.  Old Mutual Plc (OML)  , the U.K.’s third-largest insurer,
increased to the highest level since March 9, gaining 20 cents,
or 1.3 percent, to 15.17 rand. The company said today it will
pay 31.51 cents per share in dividends.  Telkom Ltd. (TKG SJ), Africa’s largest fixed-line telephone
operator, closed at its the highest level since Jan. 11,
rallying 65 cents, or 1.8 percent, to 37.65 rand, after saying
it reached an agreement to sell the CDMA business of its Multi-
Links unit in  Nigeria  to Visafone Communications Ltd. for $52
million.  Trematon Capital Investments Ltd. (TMT)  , a private
equity fund with interests in financial services and information
technology, fell the most in two months, dropping 9 cents, or 6
percent, to 1.40 rand. Earnings per share after one-time items
dropped to 2.4 cents in the period through February, from 17.7
cents a share a year earlier.  To contact the reporters on this story:
